org.phlo.tuplez
Class Executor

java.lang.Object
  org.phlo.tuplez.Executor

public class Executor
extends Object

Executes concrete Operations.

Executor instances are created from DataSources, and contain instance methods which execute concrete Operation implementations.

Executor instances or typically created by Spring. This is e.g. done by putting the following into your application context configuration XML (assuming that there is a bean named "DataSource" which defines your database connection). 

<bean id="DatabaseExecutor"
      class="org.phlo.tuplez.Executor"
>
    <property name="DataSource" ref="DataSource"/>
</bean>

iterate

public <InputType,ConcreteInputType extends InputType,OutputType,OpClassType extends Operation<InputType,OutputType>,ResultType> ResultType iterate(Class<OpClassType> opClass,
                                                                                                                                                    ConcreteInputType input,
                                                                                                                                                    IteratorProcessor<OutputType,ResultType> iteratorProcessor)
Executes a database operation using the provided instance of InputType to fill in parameters, passes an iterator over the resulting instances of OutputType to the iteratorProcessor, and returns the iteratorProcessor's result of type ResultType.

If the database operation requires no input (meaning InputType is Void) you must use iterate(opClass, iteratorProcessor) instead, since Void is uninstantiable.

It's usually easier to use collection(opClass, input) instead of using this method directly

Type Parameters:
InputType - the Operation<InputType, OutputType>'s input type
ConcreteInputType - the actual (concrete) implementation of InputType
OpClassType - the operation class'es actual type, extends Operation<InputType, OutputType>
OutputType - the Operation<InputType, OutputType>'s output type and IteratorProcessor<OutputType, ResultType>'s element type
ResultType - the IteratorProcessor<OutputType, ResultType>'s result type
Parameters:
opClass - the concrete Operation<InputType, OutputType> implementation
input - the ConcreteInputType instance used to fill in the operation's parameters
iteratorProcessor - the IteratorProcessor<OutputType, ResultType> instance
Returns:
the iteratorProcessor's result of type ResultType

get

public <InputType,ConcreteInputType extends InputType,OutputType,OpClassType extends Operation<InputType,OutputType> & ReturnsSingleRow> OutputType get(Class<OpClassType> opClass,
                                                                                                                                                       ConcreteInputType input)
Executes a single-row-returning database operation (flagged as such by implementing the interface ReturnsSingleRow) using the provided instance of InputType to fill in parameters, and returns a single OutputType instance representing the single result row, or null if no row was produced.

It is an error for an operation executed with this method to return more than one row. Doing so triggers an InvalidDataAccessApiUsageException

If the database operation requires no input (meaning <InputType is Void) you must use get(opClass) instead, since Void is uninstantiable.

key

public <InputType,ConcreteInputType extends InputType,KeyType extends Number,OpClassType extends Operation<InputType,Void> & GeneratesKey<KeyType> & ReturnsSingleRow> KeyType key(Class<OpClassType> opClass,
                                                                                                                                                                                 ConcreteInputType input)
Executes a single-key-returning database operation (flagged as such by implementing the interfaces ReturnsSingleRow) and GeneratesKey while requires no input, and returns a single KeyType instance representing the generated key. The operation's OutputType must be Void.

It is an error for an operation executed with this method to return more than one key. Doing so triggers an InvalidDataAccessApiUsageException

If the database operation requires input (meaning <InputType is not Void) you must use key(opClass, input) instead.
